<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="33" pageId="5" pageNumber="31" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1519,1785]" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,430,1519,1545]" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">Description. Male:</emphasis>
Head with fastigium narrow. Pronotum quite flat, slightly upturned at the hind margin (
<figureCitation box="[160,232,1559,1585]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="6.[151,255,1518,1542]" captionTargetBox="[318,1279,187,1505]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[318,1279,187,1507]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 6. Leptophyes sicula male, a. pronotum and elytron (lateral view), b. supra-anal plate and cerci, c. cercus, d. elytron (dorsal), e. elytron (ventral), f. stridulatory file. All detailphoto’s by R. Kleukers." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195959/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<number box="[216,232,1559,1585]" pageId="5" pageNumber="31" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
a). Elytron more or less round, with a strong bulging at the hind margin (
<figureCitation box="[1113,1185,1559,1585]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="6.[151,255,1518,1542]" captionTargetBox="[318,1279,187,1505]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[318,1279,187,1507]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 6. Leptophyes sicula male, a. pronotum and elytron (lateral view), b. supra-anal plate and cerci, c. cercus, d. elytron (dorsal), e. elytron (ventral), f. stridulatory file. All detailphoto’s by R. Kleukers." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195959/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<number box="[1169,1185,1559,1585]" pageId="5" pageNumber="31" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
e), visible part of the elytron approximately the length of the pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[753,824,1599,1625]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="6.[151,255,1518,1542]" captionTargetBox="[318,1279,187,1505]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[318,1279,187,1507]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 6. Leptophyes sicula male, a. pronotum and elytron (lateral view), b. supra-anal plate and cerci, c. cercus, d. elytron (dorsal), e. elytron (ventral), f. stridulatory file. All detailphoto’s by R. Kleukers." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195959/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<number box="[808,824,1599,1625]" pageId="5" pageNumber="31" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
a). Stridulatory file with 
<number box="[1117,1219,1599,1625]" pageId="5" pageNumber="31" value="117.0" valueMax="124.0" valueMin="110.0">110–124</number>
teeth. In the basal part of the file the teeth are narrow and irregularly spaced, in the distal 
<number box="[1046,1061,1639,1665]" pageId="5" pageNumber="31" value="2.0">2</number>
/ 
<number box="[1072,1086,1639,1665]" pageId="5" pageNumber="31" value="3.0">3</number>
part the teeth are broad and regularly spaced (
<figureCitation box="[366,440,1679,1705]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="6.[151,255,1518,1542]" captionTargetBox="[318,1279,187,1505]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[318,1279,187,1507]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 6. Leptophyes sicula male, a. pronotum and elytron (lateral view), b. supra-anal plate and cerci, c. cercus, d. elytron (dorsal), e. elytron (ventral), f. stridulatory file. All detailphoto’s by R. Kleukers." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195959/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[423,440,1679,1705]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="6.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="31" unit="g" value="6.0">6</quantity>
</figureCitation>
g). Cercus slender and evenly curved, tapering into a sharp, dark point. The cercus somewhat constricted at 
<number box="[440,450,1719,1745]" pageId="5" pageNumber="31" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[461,477,1719,1745]" pageId="5" pageNumber="31" value="2.0">2</number>
of its length (
<figureCitation box="[640,710,1719,1745]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="6.[151,255,1518,1542]" captionTargetBox="[318,1279,187,1505]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[318,1279,187,1507]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 6. Leptophyes sicula male, a. pronotum and elytron (lateral view), b. supra-anal plate and cerci, c. cercus, d. elytron (dorsal), e. elytron (ventral), f. stridulatory file. All detailphoto’s by R. Kleukers." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195959/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<number box="[694,710,1719,1745]" pageId="5" pageNumber="31" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
c). Subgenital plate long and narrow, extending beyond the tip of the cerci.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195959/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="32" targetBox="[318,1279,187,1505]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1518,1573]" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,283,1518,1542]" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">FIGURE 6.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[290,484,1519,1542]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Leptophyes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sicula">
<emphasis box="[290,484,1519,1542]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">Leptophyes sicula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
male, a. pronotum and elytron (lateral view), b. supra-anal plate and cerci, c. cercus, d. elytron (dorsal), e. elytron (ventral), f. stridulatory file. All detailphoto’s by R. Kleukers.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1615,2003]" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">
General colour in living animals light green, with numerous reddish-brown spots (
<figureCitation box="[1215,1291,1615,1641]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1156,1180]" captionTargetBox="[264,1322,439,1142]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[264,1323,439,1143]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male Leptophyes sicula, reared from nymph. Cava Grande del Cassabile, Sicily (1998). Photo Paolo Fontana." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195956/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">
Fig. 
<number box="[1274,1291,1615,1641]" pageId="6" pageNumber="32" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). Pronotum dorsally greenish with creme coloured margins. Elytron dorsally mostly brownish, with black stripe and green foremargin. In some specimens the region around the stridulatory file lighter than the surrounding area. Abdomen dorsally with red brown stripe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1615,2003]" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">
Measurements (n = 
<number box="[440,458,1764,1790]" pageId="6" pageNumber="32" value="5.0">5</number>
): body 
<quantity box="[551,731,1764,1790]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4449999999999998" metricValueMax="1.52" metricValueMin="1.3699999999999999" pageId="6" pageNumber="32" unit="mm" value="14.45" valueMax="15.2" valueMin="13.7">13.7–15.2 mm</quantity>
, pronotum 
<quantity box="[870,966,1764,1790]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="6" pageNumber="32" unit="mm" value="2.4">2.4 mm</quantity>
, visible part elytron 
<quantity box="[1219,1369,1764,1790]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.95" metricValueMax="3.2" metricValueMin="2.7" pageId="6" pageNumber="32" unit="mm" value="2.95" valueMax="3.2" valueMin="2.7">2.7–3.2 mm</quantity>
, hind femur 
<quantity box="[228,402,1801,1827]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.435" metricValueMax="1.51" metricValueMin="1.3599999999999999" pageId="6" pageNumber="32" unit="mm" value="14.35" valueMax="15.1" valueMin="13.6">13.6–15.1 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1615,2003]" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,299,1838,1864]" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">Female:</emphasis>
Head with fastigium narrow. Pronotum quite flat, not upturned at the hind margin (
<figureCitation box="[1332,1406,1839,1865]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1060,1084]" captionTargetBox="[265,1322,181,1046]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[265,1322,181,1046]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 8. Leptophyes sicula female, a. habitus (lateral view), b. pronotum and elytron (dorsal), c. ovipositor." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195961/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">
Fig. 
<number box="[1391,1406,1839,1865]" pageId="6" pageNumber="32" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
a). Visible part of the elytron approximately half of the length of the pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[1100,1174,1873,1899]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1060,1084]" captionTargetBox="[265,1322,181,1046]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[265,1322,181,1046]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 8. Leptophyes sicula female, a. habitus (lateral view), b. pronotum and elytron (dorsal), c. ovipositor." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195961/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">
Fig. 
<number box="[1159,1174,1873,1899]" pageId="6" pageNumber="32" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
b). Ovipositor evenly curved (
<figureCitation box="[248,319,1908,1934]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1060,1084]" captionTargetBox="[265,1322,181,1046]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[265,1322,181,1046]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 8. Leptophyes sicula female, a. habitus (lateral view), b. pronotum and elytron (dorsal), c. ovipositor." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195961/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">
Fig. 
<number box="[304,319,1908,1934]" pageId="6" pageNumber="32" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
c). General colour in living animals light green, with numerous reddish-brown spots (
<figureCitation box="[1335,1406,1908,1934]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1060,1084]" captionTargetBox="[265,1322,181,1046]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[265,1322,181,1046]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 8. Leptophyes sicula female, a. habitus (lateral view), b. pronotum and elytron (dorsal), c. ovipositor." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195961/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">
Fig. 
<number box="[1391,1406,1908,1934]" pageId="6" pageNumber="32" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
c). Pronotum dorsally greenish with crème coloured margins. Elytron dorsally mostly yellow-brown, with black stripe and green foremargin. Abdomen dorsally with red brown stripe.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195960/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="33" targetBox="[355,1234,194,1203]" targetPageId="7">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1229,1316]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,287,1229,1253]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33">FIGURE 7.</emphasis>
Oscillograms (200 ms) of calling song of 
<taxonomicName box="[768,970,1229,1252]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Leptophyes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sicula">
<emphasis box="[768,970,1229,1252]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="33">Leptophyes sicula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. a–d: Specimen AF: Rec. Paolo Fontana, 5.VII.1998 at 16bits/44.1kHz, 27˚C, tape PF1998-2B: 4; e–j: Specimen BF: Rec. Paolo Fontana, 3.VII.1998 at 16bits/ 44.1kHz, 27˚C, tape PF1998-2A: 13.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1362,1949]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33">
Measurements (n = 
<number box="[441,455,1362,1388]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33" value="1.0">1</number>
): body (without ovipositor) 
<quantity box="[802,912,1362,1388]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.76" pageId="7" pageNumber="33" unit="mm" value="17.6">17.6 mm</quantity>
, pronotum 
<quantity box="[1051,1147,1362,1388]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="7" pageNumber="33" unit="mm" value="3.2">3.2 mm</quantity>
, visible part elytron 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9" pageId="7" pageNumber="33" unit="mm" value="1.9">1.9 mm</quantity>
, hind femur 
<quantity box="[348,455,1400,1426]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.68" pageId="7" pageNumber="33" unit="mm" value="16.8">16.8 mm</quantity>
, ovipositor 
<quantity box="[592,686,1400,1426]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.2" pageId="7" pageNumber="33" unit="mm" value="7.2">7.2 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1362,1949]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,287,1437,1463]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33">Sound:</emphasis>
The song is a more or less regular repetition of a ticking sound, exceptionally broken in two fragments in close distance (
<figureCitation box="[486,559,1474,1500]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="7.[151,258,1229,1253]" captionTargetBox="[355,1234,194,1203]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[339,1255,182,1210]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 7. Oscillograms (200 ms) of calling song of Leptophyes sicula. a – d: Specimen AF: Rec. Paolo Fontana, 5. VII. 1998 at 16 bits / 44.1 kHz, 27 ˚ C, tape PF 1998 - 2 B: 4; e – j: Specimen BF: Rec. Paolo Fontana, 3. VII. 1998 at 16 bits / 44.1 kHz, 27 ˚ C, tape PF 1998 - 2 A: 13." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195960/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="33">
Fig. 
<number box="[542,559,1474,1500]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
). Analogous to other species of the genus it has to be regarded as a simple syllable, lasting about 
<number box="[421,495,1512,1538]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33" value="45.0" valueMax="50.0" valueMin="40.0">40–50</number>
ms. These syllables are repeated every 0,5– 
<number box="[1026,1039,1512,1538]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33" value="3.0">3</number>
s. Although the resolution of the available recordings is not sufficient, it is clear that the syllable consists at least of about 
<number box="[1253,1313,1549,1575]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33" value="11.5" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="8.0">8–15</number>
pulses. A reliable frequency spectrum could not be established, as the available recordings do not include frequencies above 
<number box="[228,257,1624,1650]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33" value="20.0">20</number>
kHz.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="33" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1362,1949]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,361,1661,1687]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33">Distribution:</emphasis>
The species is only known from the 
<typeStatus box="[847,898,1661,1687]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33">type</typeStatus>
locality Cava Grande del Cassabile in the southeast of Sicily, south of the town of Siracusa in the Monti Iblei (
<figureCitation box="[997,1087,1698,1724]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="15.[151,255,1903,1927]" captionTargetBox="[399,1201,1139,1889]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[399,1201,1139,1891]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 17. Distribution of the European Leptophyes species, a. L. albovittata, b. L. boscii and L. discoidalis (asterisk), c. L. laticauda, d. L. punctatissima, L. lisae (upturned square), L. calabra (asterisk) and L. sicula (square). Sources: Baur et al. (2006), Fontana et al. (2006), Harz (1969), Heller &amp; Willemse (1989), Kleukers et al. (1997), Maas et al. (2002), Schmidt (1989, 1990), Voisin (2006)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195970/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="33">
Fig. 
<number box="[1055,1087,1698,1724]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
d). Possibly all records of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Leptophyes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatissima">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="33">L. punctatissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of Sicily (summarized in 
<bibRefCitation author="Fontana" box="[623,859,1736,1762]" pageId="7" pageNumber="42" refString="Fontana, P., La Greca, M. &amp; Kleukers, R. (2006) Insecta Orthoptera. In: Ruffo, S. &amp; Stoch, F. (Eds). Checklist and distribution of the Italian fauna. Memorie del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale di Verona, 2. Serie, Sezione Scienze della Vita 17, 137 - 139, with data on dc-rom." type="journal article" year="2006">
Fontana 
<emphasis box="[724,783,1736,1761]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="33">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[798,859,1736,1762]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33" value="2006.0">2006</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)) refer to 
<taxonomicName box="[976,1077,1736,1761]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Leptophyes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sicula">
<emphasis box="[976,1077,1736,1761]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="33">L. sicula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but this has to be investigated further.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1362,1949]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,304,1810,1836]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33">Habitat:</emphasis>
Many nymphs were observed on small shrubs and large herbs in dense Mediterranean macchia in the upper part of the deepest and largest gorge in Sicily (cava meaning gorge in Sicily).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="33" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1362,1949]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,343,1885,1911]" pageId="7" pageNumber="33">Etymology:</emphasis>
A noun in apposition. The species is named after the island Sicily where the only known locality is situated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
